#week-title("One", "The Four Colour Stages of the Mineral Work")

=== Core Teaching

The alchemical colour sequence — Nigredo (black), Albedo (white), Citrinitas
(yellow), Rubedo (red) — applies to all three kingdoms, but achieves its most
complete and diagnostic expression in the mineral and metallic work. In the
vegetable work, the colour stages are visible in the preparation but progress
rapidly. In the mineral work, each stage may persist for months before
transitioning.

*Nigredo — The Black.* In a sealed mineral preparation, the Nigredo appears
as a darkening or blackening of the matter. In antimony work, the initial
stibnite ore is already grey-black — the Nigredo of the antimony is therefore
not a change but a confirmation of the starting material's nature. In Via
Humida mineral work with iron or copper, the Nigredo appears as the first
stage of dissolution: the matter loses its solid structure and enters the dark,
amorphous dissolved state. The Nigredo stage in a sealed digestion may produce
a black or very dark preparation that persists for weeks or months.

*Albedo — The White.* The whitening follows the Nigredo after sufficient
dissolution and purification. In a sealed vessel, it appears as a gradual
lightening of the dissolved matter: from black through grey toward white or
silver-grey. In some preparations, a white crystalline deposit appears in the
flask above the dissolved fraction — this is an early sign of Albedo.

*Citrinitas — The Yellow.* The yellowing has been the least emphasized of the
four stages in post-medieval literature, but the tradition treats it as
essential: the transition from the lunar Albedo to the solar Rubedo. It appears
as a golden-yellow tinting of the preparation after the white stage — the solar
force beginning to manifest before the full Rubedo.

*Rubedo — The Red.* The reddening is the goal: the preparation in its
highest, most elevated state. The Rubedo appears as a deepening toward red
or purple-red in the preparation. In the fullest form, the Rubedo of the
Stone produces a deep ruby-red colour of extraordinary quality.

=== Topics This Week

- The four colour stages in the mineral work: pacing and duration
- Distinguishing the Nigredo of starting material from the Nigredo of process
- The Albedo as the first sign of genuine progress in a sealed preparation
- The Citrinitas as the overlooked intermediate between Albedo and Rubedo

